topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"L'Isle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland, Durham, and Yorkshire): variant of   Lyle   and a cognate of 2 below.","French: habitational name from L'Isle or Lisle, names of several places in various parts of France, named with Old French <i>isle</i> ‘island’ (from Latin <i>insula</i>). Compare   Delisle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyle","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin): topographic or habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>del isle</i> ‘from the island’ (from Latin <i>de insula</i>), denoting someone who lived on an island or who came from a place in France named Ile, Isle, or L'Isle. The surname may also in some cases be from Lille (Nord). Compare   Lisle   and   Iles  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]},{"name":"Lile","meanings":["English and French: variant of   Lisle  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]}]},{"name":"Bouchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Michel, Normand, Pierre, Cecile, Gilles, Lucien, Alphonse, Jacques, Alain.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Burchard</i>, composed of the elements <i>burg</i> ‘protection’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’.","French: in some cases, possibly also a nickname for someone with a big mouth (in either a literal or figurative sense), from <i>bouche</i> ‘mouth’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>. Compare   Buschor  ,   Bushard  ,   Bushaw  , and   Bushor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bushard","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Bouchard  .","Possibly, in some cases, also an Americanized form of German <b>Buschard</b> (see   Bushart   2)."]},{"name":"Buschor","meanings":["Swiss German: probably a Germanized form of French   Bouchard  . Compare   Buschur   and   Bushor  ."]},{"name":"Bushore","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Bouchard  , reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. Compare   Bushor  ."]}]},{"name":"Péloquin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Normand, Andre, Fernand, Laurent, Pierre, Edouard, Lucien, Mathieu, Monique, Valmore.","French:","possibly a nickname for a miser, from a shortening of <i>pèle ocquin</i>, from <i>peler</i> ‘to remove skin or pluck hair’ + a diminutive of <i>ocque</i>, a French term from the Ottoman Turkish measure of weight <i>oka</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pelican","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Peloquin  .","Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, and Hungarian <b>Pelikán</b> or German, Croatian, and Slovenian   Pelikan   ‘pelican’.","In some cases possibly also French: nickname from <i>pélican</i>, Occitan <i>pelican</i> ‘pelican’ (see   Pelikan  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Péloquin de L'Isle Bouchard I was born in 1063, in Lisle, Loir-et-Cher, France. He married Eustachie De L'isle-Bouchard in 1087, in L'Île Bouchard, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died from 1089 to 1138."},"et":{"1063–from 1089 to 1138":"1063–1089 kuni 1138","1067–Female":"1067–Surnud","1106–1170":"1106–1170","1114–1130":"1114–1130","–Male":"Surnud","1063–1138":"1063–1138","from 1089 to 1138":"1089 kuni 1138","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1114":"1114","1067":"1067","1087":"1087","1130":"1130","1063":"1063","1170":"1170","Lisle Bourchard, Indre Et Loire Centre, France":"Lisle, Loir-et-Cher, Prantsusmaa","L'Île-Bouchard, Chinon, Indre-et-Loire, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"L'Île Bouchard, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1063–from 1089 to 1138"